    What is the main purpose of using Git?
    Git is the most commonly used version control system. Git tracks the changes you make to files, so you have a record of what has been done, and you can revert to specific versions should you ever need to. Git also makes collaboration easier, allowing changes by multiple people to all be merged into one source.

      Overview

      This PR completes the third part of the user authentication flow by implementing user session management:

      1. User signup/login with email/password form (branch: feature/user-auth-form).
      2. User signup/login with Google Sign-In (branch: feature/user-auth-google).
      3. Create/revoke user sessions and handle protected routes (branch: feature/user-auth-session) ← This PR.

      This includes handling "Continue with Google" functionality, creating/revoking user sessions upon signup or login, and integrating these flows with the UI.

      Changes Made

      Session Management

      • React Query Setup: Enables data fetching and caching for authentication-related state.
      • Token Handling:
        • Implement JWE-encrypted tokens for access and refresh tokens, stored in HTTP-only, secure cookies.
        • Add logic to refresh tokens and validate access tokens to maintain user sessions.
        • Use access tokens to fetch protected user information (e.g., /api/me endpoint).
      • Middleware:
        • Add middleware.ts to protect routes and ensure only authenticated users can access restricted pages.

      Google Sign-In Flow

      • "Continue with Google" Actions:
        • Redirect users to Google Sign-In with a dynamically generated URL.
        • On successful authentication:
          • Redirect to the api/auth/google/callback endpoint.
          • Check if the user exists:
            • Redirect new users to /signup to complete account creation.
        • Pass a JWE-encrypted token in the query parameter:
          • Includes a 15-minute expiration for security.
          • Requires a secret key for decryption, ensuring tamper-proof data.
        • Display a short signup form with email prefilled on /signup for Google-authenticated users to set a username and finalize their account creation.
        • On successful signup or login, generate new access/refresh tokens and redirect to the home page.

      Navbar Integration

      • Displays Login/Signup buttons for unauthenticated users and a Logout button for authenticated users.
      • Uses useAuthUserQuery to fetch the current user's authentication state.
      • Implements useLogOutMutation:
        • Invalidates the authUser query.
        • Removes access and refresh tokens from cookies.

      Known Issues / Improvements to Make

      Delays in UI State Updates

      • Slight delays in updating UI components after authentication state changes:
        • Navbar buttons (Login/Signup or Logout) display with a brief lag.
        • The Google signup completion form does not appear immediately upon redirect.
      • Potential Causes:
        • React Query hooks (e.g., useAuthUserQuery) may introduce delays in state updates.
        • Decrypting tokens and validating states add processing time.
        • React’s rendering flow may contribute to flickering or misaligned state updates.
